                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14460263" author="guillaume" created="Sat, 8 May 2004 13:13:17 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In fact, in CVS Head, we commented those offending lines, because we noticed that some jars delimit the entries in very different ways, so it&apos;s not that easy to parse the Class-Path attribute. For the current code in Head, look at:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://cvs.groovy.codehaus.org/groovy/groovy-core/src/main/groovy/lang/GroovyClassLoader.java?rev=1.20&amp;amp;view=auto&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://cvs.groovy.codehaus.org/groovy/groovy-core/src/main/groovy/lang/GroovyClassLoader.java?rev=1.20&amp;amp;view=auto&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Did you try with the latest groovy snapshot jar ? Since I&apos;ve fixed the deployment of the snapshot on the distribution site, you can pick it at:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://dist.codehaus.org/groovy/dist/groovy/jars/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://dist.codehaus.org/groovy/dist/groovy/jars/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460325" author="spullara" created="Sat, 8 May 2004 14:53:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;What exactly is the format you have seen that is different from the spec?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Class-Path :&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The value of this attribute specifies the relative URLs of the extensions or libraries that this application or extension needs. URLs are separated by one or more spaces. The application or extension class loader uses the value of this attribute to construct its internal search path. &lt;br/&gt;
&#160;&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.4/docs/guide/jar/jar.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.4/docs/guide/jar/jar.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Seems unambiguous. We should put the support back in with some exception handling for people that have incorrect attributes in their manifest.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460145" author="goetze" created="Sun, 9 May 2004 06:54:16 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve seen variations of comma, semicolon and space separated entities, sometimes mixtures in the same jar file.  It would definitely be possible to handle these cases; however, before we add more jars to the classpath, I think we need to look at the performance implications.  I&apos;ve commented on this in &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/GROOVY-173&quot; title=&quot;provide security sandbox for executing scripts&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;GROOVY-173&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;GROOVY-173&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and would appreciate any suggestions about how to make things more efficient. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460342" author="kos" created="Sun, 9 May 2004 08:32:46 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;yes, in 1.0-rc1 snapshot NPE has gone&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14460236" author="guillaume" created="Sun, 9 May 2004 13:03:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The NPE is fixed, and moreover, it&apos;s possible to expand the class-path even if the attribute is malformed.&lt;br/&gt;
When we add a way to provide warnings back to the user, we&apos;ll be able warn him that he uses a jar with a malformed class-path attribute.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
